Robert Owen (1771-1858) advocated the transformation of society into small, local collectives without such elaborate systems of social organization.
Owen managed mills for many years.
He transformed life in the village of New Lanark with ideas and opportunities which were at least a hundred years ahead of their time.
Child labor and corporal punishment were abolished, and villagers were provided with decent homes, schools and evening classes, free health-care, and affordable food.
