The Swedish Socialists formed a government in 1932.
They broke with economic orthodoxy during the depression and carried out extensive public works financed from government borrowing.
They emphasised large-scale intervention and the high unemployment they had inherited was eliminated by 1938.
Their success encouraged the adoption of Keynesian policies of deficit financing pursued by almost all Western countries after World War II.
